         <div type="apparatus">
            <head>Apparatus</head>
            <app loc="1"><rdg resp="#applebaum1954">Μνήσθηος</rdg>
               <rdg resp="#gl-jmr1983">Μνήσθηθε<unclear>ι</unclear></rdg></app>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve"><head>Translations</head>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" source="#jmr1960"><p>Remember Rufus, God of rest</p></div>
            <div type="translation" source="#gl-jmr1983" xml:lang="de"><p>Gedenke des Rufus, Gott, (seines) Schlafes</p></div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" source="#jmr-jbwp-rgg2003"><p>Remember the rest of Rufus, God</p></div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" source="#cdlBE"><p>Dieu, n'oublie pas le repos éternel de Rufus</p></div>
         </div>
         
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>Line 1: apparently for μνήσθητι; for a summary of the material on this formula in pagan, 
               Jewish and Christian prayer see A. D. Nock <title level="j">JTS</title> XXX (1929) 393f.
               Since there are no Christian symbols here, Applebaum regarded the text as Jewish, but Nock notes that in Syria the form 
               μνήσθητι is limited to Christian inscriptions and it may be that Cabrol Leclerq 
               are right to take it as Christian. See also the discussion by Lüderitz.</p>
            <p>Line 3: for κοιμήσεως.</p>
         </div>
         
